#### Category 4: IaC Modules - Pulumi (Critical - 13.32% total)

**Module Files (6.66%):**
- [ ] `iac/pulumi/module/main.go` exists
- [ ] `iac/pulumi/module/locals.go` exists
- [ ] `iac/pulumi/module/outputs.go` exists

**Module Comment Quality (scored as part of Module Files):**
- [ ] Module code carries authoring comments that explain *why* / trade-offs / provider quirks / non-obvious ordering, not line-by-line narration
- [ ] Comments reach the density and intent of the `spec.proto` field-comment standard (these modules render on the public catalog)
- [ ] Not merely present: a working but uncommented or narration-only module does NOT earn full Module Files credit

**Reference:** See `architecture/deployment-component.md` §4.1 Code Quality ("Well-Commented Module Code") for the module-comment bar.

**Entrypoint Files (6.66%):**
- [ ] `iac/pulumi/main.go` exists AT THE ROOT and declares `package main`
- [ ] NO `iac/pulumi/main/` subdir and NO `iac/pulumi/entrypoint/` subdir exist
      (a misplaced entrypoint in a subdir is a FAIL even if `main.go` exists there -- the
      release build is non-recursive and only consumes the root `iac/pulumi/` package)
- [ ] `iac/pulumi/Pulumi.yaml` exists
- [ ] `iac/pulumi/Makefile` exists
- [ ] Release-equivalent build passes:
      `go build -o /dev/null ./apis/dev/planton/provider/<provider>/<component>/v1/iac/pulumi`
      (this is the EXACT command the release pipeline runs; presence checks alone are not
      sufficient -- a component can have files yet still fail this build)

**Scoring:** Each sub-category scored independently. Entrypoint structure (root `package main`,
no subdir) and the release-equivalent build are CRITICAL: a component that fails either cannot
be released and must be reported as a critical gap regardless of other scores.

#### Category 5: IaC Modules - Terraform (Critical - 4.44%)

**Checks:**
- [ ] `iac/tf/variables.tf` exists and is substantial (>1KB)
- [ ] `iac/tf/provider.tf` exists
- [ ] `iac/tf/locals.tf` exists
- [ ] `iac/tf/main.tf` exists and is substantial (>1KB)
- [ ] `iac/tf/outputs.tf` exists

**Module Comment Quality (scored as part of this category):**
- [ ] HCL carries authoring comments that explain *why* / trade-offs / provider quirks / non-obvious ordering, not line-by-line narration (the same module-comment bar as the Pulumi module)
- [ ] Not merely present: a working but uncommented or narration-only module does NOT earn full credit

**Reference:** See `architecture/deployment-component.md` §4.1 Code Quality ("Well-Commented Module Code") for the module-comment bar.

**Scoring:** Pass all checks = 4.44%, partial = proportional

#### Category 5b: Cross-Engine IaC Parity (Critical GATE — no separate weight)

This category does NOT add a new percentage slice. It is a **gate** on the two IaC
categories above: the Pulumi (Category 4) and Terraform (Category 5) scores assume the two
engines implement the SAME contract. Any **undocumented** divergence is a critical defect
that (a) is reported under "Critical Gaps", and (b) caps BOTH IaC categories at ⚠️ Partial
(or ❌ if a divergence would actually misdeploy — wrong namespace, wrong selector, missing
feature, or empty stack-output field). A documented `PARITY-EXCEPTION:` (present in BOTH
modules, output-neutral, minimal) is NOT a defect.

**How to evaluate (read both modules; neither is privileged — compare against the proto contract + intended behavior):**

Open `iac/pulumi/module/*.go` and `iac/tf/*.tf` and compare each dimension from
`pkg/iac/MODULE_PARITY.md`. For each, record MATCH / DIVERGES (undocumented) / EXCEPTION (documented):

- [ ] **Namespace / scope source** — both read the same spec field (e.g. `spec.namespace`),
      not a derived name or resource id.
- [ ] **Resource naming basis** — created objects (operator CRs, secret names, pod
      annotations) key off the same field on both sides (`metadata.name` is the established basis).
- [ ] **Labels** — identical keys AND values (the `kuberneteslabelkeys` set; kind value is the
      `CloudResourceKind` enum string, not an ad-hoc literal; conditional labels under the same condition).
- [ ] **Pod/service selectors** — match the labels the operator/chart actually applies to
      workload pods (a selector built from resource-identity labels silently matches zero pods).
- [ ] **Spec feature coverage** — every `spec.proto` field is honored by BOTH engines
      (backup, restore/standby, ingress, env injection, sizing, ...). A field implemented on
      one side and ignored on the other is a parity defect even if both `validate`.
- [ ] **Dependency ordering** — the same edges exist (`pulumi.DependsOn` ↔ `depends_on` /
      `metadata.relationships`).
- [ ] **Stack outputs** — both engines emit shapes that flatten onto the SAME
      `*_stack_outputs.proto` fields. VERIFY with the automated guard, not by eye:
      ```bash
      planton validate-outputs --kind <Kind> --module-dir apis/.../v1/iac/tf --sample-outputs <sample>.json
      ```
      A field that stays empty (e.g. a flat `password_secret_name` output that never reaches the
      nested `password_secret{name,key}` proto field) is a parity defect. If a per-kind case
      exists in `pkg/outputs/conformance_test.go`, note whether it passes; if it does not exist,
      flag that as a follow-up to add.

**Gate outcome (record this explicitly):**
- **PARITY ✅** — every dimension MATCHES or is a documented EXCEPTION.
- **PARITY ⚠️** — one or more undocumented divergences that do not change the deployed
  outcome (cosmetic label/comment drift). Cap Categories 4 & 5 at Partial.
- **PARITY ❌** — at least one divergence that would misdeploy (wrong namespace/selector,
  missing feature, or an unpopulated stack-output field). Report as a Critical Gap and mark
  Categories 4 & 5 ❌.

